{"title_page": "Paleobiota of the Posidonia Shale", "text_new": "[[File:Seironcrinus subangularis Miller, die gr\u00f6\u00dfte fossile Seelilien-Kolonie (18 x 6 m).jpg|thumb|380px|right|18x6 m fossilized floating wood ([[Araucarioxylon]]), with Crinoids attached ([[Pentacrinites]] & [[Seirocrinus]]). It is one of the most emblematic fossils of the formation, where the anoxic seas of the lower toarcian lead to an exquisite preservation.]]\n{{Paleontology}}\nThe [[Posidonia Shale]]  is a [[geological formation]] of southwestern [[Germany]], northern [[Switzerland]], western [[Czech Republic]], northwestern [[Austria]], southeast [[Luxembourg]] and the [[Netherlands]], that spans about 3 million years during the [[Early Jurassic]] period (early [[Toarcian]] stage). It is known for its detailed [[fossil]]s, especially sea fauna, listed below.\n\n=== Algae ===\nIncludes abundant variety of algae, such as the genus of colonial Green algae [[Botryococcus]],<ref>Gorbanenko, O. O., & Ligouis, B. (2014). Changes in optical properties of liptinite macerals from early mature to post mature stage in Posidonia Shale (Lower Toarcian, NW Germany). International journal of coal geology, 133, 47-59.</ref> or the unicellular algal bodies [[Tasmanites]], and other small examples. Algae are a good reference for changes on the oxygen conditions along the Toarcian.<ref>Schouten, S., van Kaam-Peters, H. M., Rijpstra, W. I. C., Schoell, M., & Damste, J. S. S. (2000). Effects of an oceanic anoxic event on the stable carbon isotopic composition of early Toarcian carbon. American Journal of Science, 300(1), 1\u201322.</ref>\n\n{{paleobiota-key-compact}}\n\n====Rhodophyta====\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Genus\n! Species\n! Location\n! Stratigraphic position\n! Material\n! Notes\n! Images\n|-\n|style=\"background:#E6E6E6;\"|\n''Cf. [[Rhodophyta]]''<ref>Ruebsam, W., & Schwark, L. (2017). Phytoplankton community dynamics during the Early Toarcian Oceanic Anoxic Event deduced from high-resolution biomarker investigation. In Proceedings of the 1st International Workshop on the Toarcian Oceanic Anoxic Event (IW-TOAE): Impact on Marine Carbon Cycle and Ecosystems, IGCP-655, Ja\u00e9n (pp. 101\u2013102).</ref>\n|style=\"background:#E6E6E6;\"|\n*''Cf. Rhodophyta sp.''\n''\n|style=\"background:#E6E6E6;\"|\n* Banz\n* Holzmaden\n|style=\"background:#E6E6E6;\"|\n|style=\"background:#E6E6E6;\"|\nSeveral Specimens\n|style=\"background:#E6E6E6;\"|\nPossible affinities with [[Rhodophyta]]. Are among the few complete specimens of Algae found on lower Jurassic sediments, being called \"Seegrasblatt\" (Seagrass leaf), have more in common with modern [[Chondria (alga)|Chondria]] dasyphylla, ranging from 25 cm to near 1 m long. Its affinities haven\u00b4t been proved. There are several specimens that resemble the also modern [[Delesseria]] sinuosa.\n|style=\"background:#E6E6E6;\"|\n[[File:Seegrasblatt.jpg|thumb|center|195px|''Seegrasblatt'', possible Cf.Rhodophyta exposed in Banz Abbey]]\n|-\n|}\n\n=== Plantae ===\nThe main source of Terrestrial land for the origin of the flora comes from the [[Regensburg bight]] at the margin of the [[Bohemian Massif]]. The Environment was part of the coast called [[Vindelician Land]], composed of large seashore environments, including [[River Delta]]s, [[Mangrove]]s, [[Lagoon]]s, Brackish deposits and other similar. The wood from the terrestrial margin hasn\u00b4t been studied, altrougth the ferns have been revieved.<ref>AMMON VON L. 1875. Die Jura Ablagerungen zwischen Regensburg und Passau. Theodor Ackermann, M\u00fcnchen</ref> The locality of [[Kerkhofen]] shows also influences of fluvial currents from the Massif.<ref>BRACH ERT Th. 1987. MakrofossilfUhrung der \"Siemensi-Geoden\" (Mittlerer Lias Epsilon, Unteres Toarcium) von KerkhofeniOberpfalz ( Bayern) : Neue Insekten- und Pflanzenfunde. Geologische Bl\u00e4tter NO-Bayern, 37(3-4) : 217\u2013240.</ref>\n\n====Equisetaceae====\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Genus\n! Species\n! Location\n! Stratigraphic position\n! Material\n! Notes\n! Images\n|-\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n''[[Equisetites]]''\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n*''Equisetites arenaceus''\n*''Equisetites sp.''\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n*Several locations.<ref name=\"Wilde\">Wilde, V. (2001). Die Landpflanzen-Taphoz\u00f6nose aus dem Posidonienschiefer des Unteren Jura (Schwarzer Jura [Epsilon], Unter-Toarcium) in Deutschland und ihre Deutung. Staatliches Museum f\u00fcr Naturkunde.</ref>\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\nLeaves and Branches.\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\nAffinities with [[Equisetaceae]]. Among the most common flora found on the Posidonia Shale, includes several specimens found on considered Blackish waters, being probably tolerant to high salinity environments.<ref>SALFELD, H. (1907): Fossile Land-Pflanzen der R\u00e4t- und Juraformation S\u00fcdwestdeutschlands. \u2013 Palaeontographica, 54/4: 163\u2013204, Taf. 14\u201322; Stuttgart. \u2013 (1909): Beitr\u00e4ge zur Kenntnis jurassischer Pflanzenreste aus Norddeutschland. \u2013 Palaeontographica, 56/1: 1\u201335, 2 Abb., Taf. 1\u20136. Stuttgart.</ref>\n| style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n[[File:Equisetites arenaceus 65.jpg|thumb|center|195px|''[[Equisetites]]'' arenaceus specimen]] \n|-\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n''[[Neocalamites]]''<ref>BRACHERT, T. C. (1987): Makrofossilf\u00fchrung der \u201eSiemensi-Geoden\u201c (Mittlerer Lias Epsilon, Unteres Toarcium) von Kerkhofen/Oberpfalz (Bayern): Neue Insekten- und Pflanzenfunde. \u2013 Geologische Bl\u00e4tter f\u00fcr Nordost-Bayern und angrenzende Gebiete, 37(3/4): 217\u2013240, 3 Abb., 2 Tab., Taf. 17\u201320; Erlangen.</ref>\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n*''Neocalamites merianii''\n*''Neocalamites sp.''\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n*Several locations.\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\nLeaves and Branches\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\nAffinities with [[Equisetaceae]].\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n[[File:Neocalamites merianii.JPG|thumb|center|195px|''[[Neocalamites]]'' merianii specimen]]   \n|-\n|}\n\n==== Filicopsida====\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Genus\n! Species\n! Location\n! Stratigraphic position\n! Material\n! Notes\n! Images\n|-\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n''[[Cladophlebis]]''<ref name=\"Vogellehner82\">Vogellehner, D. (1982). Zur Anatomie und Systematik von \u00abTreibh\u00f6lzern\u00bb aus dem Posidonienschiefer von Holzmaden (Schw\u00e4b. Alb).</ref>\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n*''Cladophlebis distans''\n*''Cladophlebis denticulata'' \n*''Cladophlebis haiburnenss''\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n*Holzmaden\n*Regensburg\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\nMostly leaves.\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\nAffinities with [[Osmundaceae]]. The main confirmed fern reported from the formation, being found on layers proximal to the Bohemian Massif, the dry land environment more proximal to the Posidonia Shale. \n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n[[File:Cladophlebis distans.jpg|thumb|center|195px|''[[Cladophlebis]]''  distans specimen]]\n|-\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n''[[Dictyophyllum]]''<ref name=\"Vogellehner82\"/>\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n*''Dictyophyllum acutilobum'' \n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n*Holzmaden\n*Regensburg\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\nMostly leaves.\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\nAffinities with [[Dipteridaceae]]. It\u00b4s  remains are rare.\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n[[File:Dictyophyllum acutilobum.JPG|thumb|center|195px|''[[Dictyophyllum]]'' acutilobum specimen]]\n|-\n|}\n\n====Peltaspermales====\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Genus\n! Species\n! Location\n! Stratigraphic position\n! Material\n! Notes\n! Images\n|-\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n''[[Pachypteris]]''<ref>B\u00f6ttcher, R. (1998): Leben und Tod im Meer des Posidonienschiefers. - In: E. P. J. Heizmann (Hrsg.): Erdgeschichte Mitteleurop\u00e4ischer Regionen (2). Vom Schwarzwald zum Ries, S. 83-96, 25 Abb.; M\u00fcnchen (Pfeil).</ref>\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n*''Pachypteris sp.''\n''\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n*Holzmaden\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\nOne specimen of pteridosperm frond.\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\nAffinities with [[Umkomasiaceae]]. It is related to the large Tree ferns of the Triassic & Jurassic. Includes several species from the Triassic to the Cretaceous only on Europe. Posidonia Shale Specimen is characterized for its large size.\n| style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n[[File:Pachypteris sp.jpg|thumb|center|195px|The only ''[[Pachypteris]]'' specimen know from the Posidonia Shale]]\n|-\n|}\n\n====Cycadeoidophyta====\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Genus\n! Species\n! Location\n! Stratigraphic position\n! Material\n! Notes\n! Images\n|-\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n''[[Otozamites]]''<ref name=\"Kurr\">KURR, J. G. (1845): Beitr\u00e4ge zur fossilen Flora der Juraformation W\u00fcrttembergs. \u2013 Anhang\nan: Einladungs-Schrift zu der Feier des Geburtsfestes Sr. Majest\u00e4t des K\u00f6nigs Wilhelm von W\u00fcrttemberg in der k\u00f6nigl. polytechnischen Schule zu Stuttgart den 27. September 1845: 1\u201317, 3 Taf.; Stuttgart (Guttenberg).</ref><ref>K\u00fcpper, K. (1968). Die Gattung Otozamites. Taxon, 17(5), 548\u2013552.</ref>\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n*''Otozamites gracilis''\n*''Otozamites bechei''\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n*Several locations.<ref name=\"Wilde\"/>\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\nLeaves\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\nAffinities with [[Bennettitales]]. It is the most abundant medium-sized plant on the environment. Found specially on seashore depositional settings, but also on deltaic and lagoonar environments.\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n[[File:Otozamites gracilis.jpg|thumb|center|195px|''[[Otozamites]]'' gracilis specimen from the Posidonia Shale]]\n|-\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n''[[Pterophyllum]]''<ref name=\"Kurr\"/>\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n*''Pterophyllum acutifolium''\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n*Several locations.<ref name=\"Wilde\"/>\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\nLeaves\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\nAffinities with [[Bennettitales]] \n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n[[File:Pterophyllum jaegeri 4556.jpg|thumb|center|195px|''[[Pterophyllum]]'' fossil]]  \n|-\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n''[[Zamites]]''<ref name=\"Kurr\"/>\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n*''Zamites mandelslohi''\n*''Zamites oblongifolius''\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n*Several locations.<ref name=\"Wilde\"/>\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\nLeaves\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\nAffinities with [[Bennettitales]]\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n[[File:Zamites mandelslohi.jpg|thumb|center|195px|''[[Zamites]]'' mandelslohi specimen]]\n|-\n|}\n\n====Pinophyta====\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Genus\n! Species\n! Location\n! Stratigraphic position\n! Material\n! Notes\n! Images\n|-\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n''[[Pagiophyllum]]''<ref name=\"Kurr\"/><ref>SALFELD, Palaeontographica, 54(4): 186\u2013188, Taf. 18</ref>\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n*''Pagiophyllum kurri''\n*''Pagiophyllum araucarinum''<ref>Saporta. \u2013 BARALE, Documents des Laboratoires de G\u00e9ologie Lyon, 81: 172\u2013177, Abb. 45, Taf. 49\u201350.</ref>\n*''Pagiophyllum sp.''\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n*Several locations.<ref name=\"Wilde\"/>\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\nLeaves\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\nAffinities with [[Araucariaceae]]\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n[[File:Koniferenblatt Pagiophyllum kurri.jpg|thumb|center|195px|''[[Pagiophyllum]]'' kurri specimen from Banz]] \n|-\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n''[[Cupressites]]''\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n*''Cupressites sp.''\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n*Several locations.<ref name=\"Wilde\"/>\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\nLeaves\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\nAffinities with [[Cupressaceae]]\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n|-\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n''[[Widdringtonites]]''<ref>URLICHS, WILD & ZIEGLER, Stuttgarter Beitr. Naturkde.,Reihe C, 11: Abb. 50.</ref>\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n*''Widdringtonites liasinus''\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n*Several locations.<ref name=\"Wilde\"/>\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\nLeaves\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\nA possible ancestral member of the [[Sequoioideae]] inside [[Cupressaceae]]. Was originally related to the genus  \"[[Quasisequoia]]\" couttsiae, but then changed to a sister taxa to [[Sequoia jeholensis]]. The later studies still suggest affinities with large modern redwoods. Probably the earliest member of the Sequoia tribe, distinct from Sequoiadendron and Metasequoia. \n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n[[File:Widdringtonites liasinus.JPG|thumb|center|195px|''[[Widdringtonites]]'' liasinus specimen from the Posidonia Shale]] \n|-\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n''[[Circoporoxylon]]''<ref>S\u00fcss, H., & Philippe, M. (1993). Holzanatomische Untersuchungen an einem fossilen Holz, Circoporoxylon grandiporosum M\u00fcller\u2010Stoll et Schultze\u2010Motel, aus dem Unteren Jura von Frankreich Mit 4 Abbildungen, einer Tabelle und 2 Tafeln. Feddes Repertorium, 104(7\u20108), 451\u2013463.</ref>\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n*''Circoporoxylon grandiporosum''\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n*Several locations.<ref name=\"Wilde\"/>\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\nFossil wood\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\nAffinities with [[Podocarpaceae]]\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n|-\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n''[[Cupressinoxylon]]''\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n*''Cupressinoxylon sp.''\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n*Banz<ref name=\"Wilde\"/>\n*Altdorf\n*Regensburg\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\nFossil wood\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\nAffinities with [[Sequoioideae]] inside [[Cupressaceae]]. Large wood with a morphology similar to the modern genus [[Sequoia sempervirens]]. Probably related to ''Widdringtonites liasinus'', representing the earliest representatives of the Sequoia tribe.\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n|-\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n''[[Podocarpoxylon]]''\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n*''cf. Podocarpoxylon sp.''\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n*Banz<ref name=\"Wilde\"/>\n*Altdorf\n*Regensburg\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\nFossil Wood\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\nAffinities with [[Podocarpaceae]]\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n[[File:Podocarpoxylon marchesoni.JPG|thumb|center|195px|''[[Podocarpoxylon]]'' specimen]]\n|-\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n''[[Protocupressinoxylon]]''<ref>SCHULTZE-MOTEL, J. (1960): Anatomische Untersuchungen an mesozoischen Gymnospermen-H\u00f6lzern. \u2013 Dissertation P\u00e4dagogische Hochschule Potsdam. 156 S., 25 Taf.; Potsdam. \u2013 [Unver\u00f6ffentlicht; Zitat nach VOGELLEHNER (1982), die betreffende Arbeit konnte bisher nicht eingesehen werden] \u2013 (1962): Anatomische Untersuchungen an mesozoischen Gymnospermen-H\u00f6lzern. \u2013 wilde, landpflanzen-taphocoenose aus dem posidonienschiefer 11 Wissenschaftliche Zeitschrift der P\u00e4dagogischen Hochschule Potsdam. Mathematischnaturwissenschaftliche Reihe, 7(1961/62): 343\u2013344; Potsdam. \u2013 [Autorreferat der unver\u00f6ffentlichten Dissertation]</ref>\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n*''Protocupressinoxylon catenatum''\n*''Protocupressinoxylon liasinum''\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n*Holzmaden.<ref name=\"Wilde\"/>\n*Banz\n*Altdorf\n*Regensburg\n*Bohemia\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\nFossil wood from trunk rafts\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\nAffinities with [[Podocarpaceae]]. Resembles [[Podocarpus totara]], and includes large sized trunks up to 1.7 m tall and 45&nbsp;cm wide. Large medium to large sized trees (25 m) that extent along the coastal lines of the Vindelician land. The wood from tose trunks shows insect activity, such as wood Vasps and Beetles, that had been found on the Posidonia Shale.\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n[[File:Protocupressinoxylon catenatum.JPG|thumb|center|195px|''[[Protocupressinoxylon]]'' catenatum specimen from Regensburg]]\n|-\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n''\"[[Protopinaceae]]\"''<ref>Mueller-Stoll, W. R. (1986). Evolutionary trends in gymnospermous wood structures during Mesozoic-Protopinaceous woods in the German Jurassic.</ref>\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n*''Protopinaceae sp.''\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n*Holzmaden.<ref name=\"Wilde\"/>\n*Banz\n*Altdorf\n*Regensburg\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\nFossil wood from trunk rafts\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\nDubious genera with possible affinities with the triassic wood [[Woodworthia]]. Protopinaceae is an invalid group of mostly Paleozoic Woods.<ref>Bamford, M. K., Philippe, M., & Th\u00e9venard, F. (2016). Long overdue extinction of the Protopinaceae. Review of palaeobotany and palynology, 234, 25\u201330.</ref>\n|\n[[File:Woodworthia, Late Jurassic, Chinle Formation, Petrified Forest Member, Deschutes River Canyon, Deschutes County, Oregon, USA - Houston Museum of Natural Science - DSC01832.JPG|thumb|center|195px|''[[Woodworthia]]'', example of Protopinaceae]]\n|-\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n''[[Phyllocladoxylon]]''<ref name=\"Vogellehner82\"/>\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n*''Phyllocldoxylon sp.''\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n*Several locations.<ref name=\"Vogellehner82\"/>\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\nFossil wood from trunk rafts\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\nAffinities with [[Podocarpaceae]]. Similar to the modern [[Phyllocladus aspleniifolius]]. \n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n|-\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n''[[Protophyllocladoxylon]]''<ref name=\"Vogellehner82\"/>\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n*''Protophyllocladoxylon franconicum''\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n*Several locations.<ref name=\"Wilde\"/><ref name=\"Vogellehner82\"/>\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\nFossil wood from trunk rafts\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\nAffinities with [[Podocarpaceae]]. Resembles the modern [[Phyllocladus hypophyllus]].\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n|-\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n''[[Taxodioxylon]]''<ref>M\u00dcLLER-STOLL, W. R. & SCHULTZE-MOTEL, J.(1990): Gymnospermen-H\u00f6lzer des Deutschen Jura. Teil 3: Abietoid (modern) get\u00fcpfelte H\u00f6lzer. \u2013 Zeitschrift der deutschen geologischen Gesellschaft, 141/1\u20132: 61\u201377, 2 Abb., 2 Taf.; Hannover</ref>\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n*''cf. Taxodioxylon''\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n*Holzmaden.<ref name=\"Wilde\"/>\n*Banz\n*Altdorf\n*Regensburg\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\nFossil wood from trunk rafts\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\nAffinities with the [[Taxodioideae]] family inside [[Cupressaceae]]. Resembles the modern genus [[Cryptomeria]]. Large trees probably related to the coastal settings. \n| style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n|-\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n''[[Araucarioxylon]]''<ref name=\"Crino0\">Matzke, A. T., & Maisch, M. W. (2019). Palaeoecology and taphonomy of a Seirocrinus (Echinodermata: Crinoidea) colony from the Early Jurassic Posidonienschiefer Formation (Early Toarcian) of Dotternhausen (SW Germany). Neues Jahrbuch f\u00fcr Geologie und Pal\u00e4ontologie-Abhandlungen, 291(1), 89\u2013107.</ref>\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n*''cf. Araucarioxylon''\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n*Holzmaden.<ref name=\"Crino0\"/>\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\nFossil wood from trunk rafts. Includes the largest know rafting wood on the fossil record, with a length of 13 m. The rafts where populated with Crinoid colonies, and a wide variety of organisms.\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\nAffinities with [[Araucariaceae]]\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n[[File:Araucarioxylon arizonicum reconstruccion.jpg|thumb|center|195px|''[[Araucarioxylon]]'' reconstruccion]]\n|-\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n''[[Dadoxylon]]''\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n*''Dadoxylon sp.''\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n*Holzmaden.<ref name=\"Wilde\"/>\n*Banz\n*Altdorf\n*Regensburg\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\nFossil wood from trunk rafts\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\nAffinities with [[Araucariaceae]], resembling the modern [[Wollemia]].\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n[[File:Nadelbaum Dadoxylon Stammfragment.jpg|thumb|center|195px|''[[Dadoxylon]]'' sp. from Banz]] \n|-\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n''[[Agathoxylon]]''\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n*''Agathoxylon agathiforme''<ref>Philippe, M., Barbacka, M., Gradinaru, E., Iamandei, E., Iamandei, S., K\u00e1zm\u00e9r, M., ... & Zato\u0144, M. (2006). Fossil wood and Mid-Eastern Europe terrestrial palaeobiogeography during the Jurassic\u2013Early Cretaceous interval. Review of Palaeobotany and Palynology, 142(1-2), 15\u201332.</ref>\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n*Holzmaden\n*Regensburg\n*Banz\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\nFossil wood from trunk rafts\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\nAffinities with [[Araucariaceae]], resembling the modern [[Agathis]].\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n|-\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n''[[Simplicioxylon]]''<ref>Philippe, M., Zijlstra, G., Barbacka, M., & Greguss. (1999). Greguss's morphogenera of homoxylous fossil woods: a taxonomic and nomenclatural review. Taxon, 667-676.</ref><ref>Philippe, M. (1991). Bois fossiles du jurassique de Franche-Comt\u00e9 (Doctoral dissertation, Lyon 1).</ref><ref>Polg\u00e1ri, M., Philippe, M., Sz\u00e1bo-Drubina, M., & T\u00f3th, M. (2005). Manganese-impregnated wood from a Toarcian manganese ore deposit, Epleny mine, Bakony Mts., Transdanubia, Hungary. Neues Jahrbuch f\u00fcr Geologie und Pal\u00e4ontologie-Monatshefte, 175\u2013192.</ref>\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n*''Simplicioxylon wurtembergicum''<ref>Philippe, M., Pacyna, G., Wawrzyniak, Z., Barbacka, M., Boka, K., Filipiak, P., ... & Uhl, D. (2015). News from an old wood\u2014Agathoxylon keuperianum (Unger) nov. comb. in the Keuper of Poland and France. Review of Palaeobotany and Palynology, 221, 83\u201391.</ref> \n*''Simplicioxylon cf.hungaricum''\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n*Holzmaden.\n*Banz\n*Altdorf\n*Regensburg\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\nFossil wood from trunk rafts\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\nAffinities with [[Cheirolepidiaceae]]\n| style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n|-\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n''[[Xenoxylon]]''<ref>Philippe, M., & Thevenard, F. (1996). Distribution and palaeoecology of the Mesozoic wood genus Xenoxylon: palaeoclimatological implications for the Jurassic of Western Europe. Review of Palaeobotany and Palynology, 91(1-4), 353\u2013370.</ref><ref>Mtiller-Stoll, W.R. and Schultze-Motel, J., 1988. Gymnospermen H\u00f6lzer des deutschen Jura. I: Xenoxylon und Dadoxylon. Z. Dtsch. Geol. Ges., 139:63 81.</ref>\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n*''Xenoxylon cf. barberi''\n*''Xenoxylon ellipticum''\n*''Xenoxylon latiporosum''\n*''Xenoxylon cf. latiporosum ''\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n*Holzmaden.<ref name=\"Wilde\"/><ref>Hallam, A. (1998). The determination of Jurassic environments using palaeoecological methods. Bulletin de la Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 g\u00e9ologique de France, 169(5), 681\u2013687.</ref>\n*Banz\n*Altdorf\n*Regensburg\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\nFossil wood\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\nAffinities with [[Coniferales]]. It is the more abundant genus of wood present on the Posidonia Shale.\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n|-\n|}\n\n==Invertebrata==\n\n=== Annelida ===\n\n====Annelidan ichnofossils====\n{| class = \"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Genus\n! Species\n! Stratigraphic position\n! Material\n! Notes\n! Images\n|-\n|style=\"background:#FEF6E4;\" |\n[[Chondrites]]<ref>Simpson, S. (1956). On the trace-fossil Chondrites. Quarterly Journal of the Geological Society, 112(1-4), 475\u2013499.</ref>\n|style=\"background:#FEF6E4;\" |\n*''Chondrites bollensis'' \n|style=\"background:#FEF6E4;\" |\n* Holzmaden\n* Banz\n|style=\"background:#FEF6E4;\" |\nBurrowing and track ichnofossils\n|style=\"background:#FEF6E4;\" |\nBurrow-like ichnofossils. Interpreted as the feeding burrow of a sediment-ingesting animal.<ref>Osgood, R. G. (1975). The history of invertebrate ichnology. In The study of trace fossils (pp. 3\u201312). Springer, Berlin, Heidelberg.</ref> A more recent study has find that [[Scoloplos]] armiger and [[Heteromastus]] filiformis, occurring in the German [[Wadden Sea]] in the lower parts of tidal flats, make burrows that are homonymous with numerous trace fossils of the ichnogenus.<ref>Hertweck, G., Wehrmann, A., & Liebezeit, G. (2007). Bioturbation structures of polychaetes in modern shallow marine environments and their analogues to Chondrites group traces. Palaeogeography, Palaeoclimatology, Palaeoecology, 245(3-4), 382\u2013389.</ref>\n|style=\"background:#FEF6E4;\" |\n[[File:Chondrites.JPG|thumb|center|195px|Illustration of Chondrites bollensis]]\n|-\n|}\n\n====Polychaeta====\n{| class = \"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Genus\n! Species\n! Stratigraphic position\n! Material\n! Notes\n! Images\n|-\n|style=\"background:#E6E6E6;\"|\n[[Serpula]]?<ref>W. Ohmert, V. Allia C. Arias et al. 1996. Die Grenzziehung Unter-/Mitteljura (Toarcium/Aalenium) bei Wittnau und Fuentelsaz [Determinig the boundary between Toarcium/Aalenium near Wittnau and Fuentelsaz]. Informationen Geologisches Landesamt Baden-W\u00fcrttemberg 8:1\u201352</ref>\n|style=\"background:#E6E6E6;\"|\n*''Serpula sp.'' \n|style=\"background:#E6E6E6;\"|\n* Kernbohrung Wittnau\n* Banz\n|style=\"background:#E6E6E6;\"|\nMultiple Specimens.\n|style=\"background:#E6E6E6;\"|\nA [[Sessility (zoology)|sessile]], [[Marine (ocean)|marine]] [[Annelida|annelid]] [[tube worm (body plan)|tube worm]]. Its affinities with the genus Serpula are controversial, since the genus is known mostly since Creataceus strata. Altrougth there are other fossils assigned to the genus on same age deposits of France.<ref>F. Papier. 2001. Die Gundershoffener Klamm. Fossilien 6/01:368\u2013374</ref>\n|style=\"background:#E6E6E6;\"|\n[[File:Serpula vermicularis 2 Linnaeus, 1767.jpg|thumb|center|195px|Head of a modern Serpula vermicularis]]\n|-\n|\n[[Filogranula]]<ref>A. Goldfuss, Petrefacta Germaniae. I. Divisio secunda: Radiariorum Reliquiae\u2014Strahlenthiere der Vorwelt (Arnz & Co, Dusseldorf, 1831), pp. 165\u2013240</ref><ref>Ippolitov, A. P., Vinn, O., Kupriyanova, E. K., J\u00e4ger, M. (2014): Written in stone: history of serpulid polychaetes through time. \u2013 Memoirs of Museum Victoria, 71: 123\u2013159</ref>\n|\n*''Filogranula tricristata'' \n|\n* Holzmaden\n* Aldortf\n* Banz\n|\nMultiple Specimens.\n|\nA [[Sessility (zoology)|sessile]], [[Marine (ocean)|marine]] [[Annelida|annelid]] [[tube worm (body plan)|tube worm]].\n|\n|-\n|\n[[Tetraserpula]]<ref>K.O.A. Parsch. 1956. Die Serpulidenfauna des s\u00fcdwestdeutschen Jura. Palaeontographica Abteilung A 107:211\u2013240</ref>\n|\n*''Tetraserpula quadrisulcata'' \n|\n* Holzmaden\n* Banz\n|\nMultiple Specimens.\n|\nA [[Sessility (zoology)|sessile]], [[Marine (ocean)|marine]] [[Annelida|annelid]] [[tube worm (body plan)|tube worm]].\n|\n|-\n|\n[[Glomerula]]<ref>J\u00e4ger, M. (2004). \"Serpulidae und Spirorbidae (Polychaeta sedentaria) aus Campan und Maastricht von Norddeutschland, den Niederlanden, Belgien und angrenzenden Gebieten\". Geologisches Jahrbuch. A 157: 121\u2013249.</ref>\n|\n*''Glomerula plexus'' \n|\n* Holzmaden\n|\nMultiple Specimens.\n|\nA [[polychaete|polychaete worm]] of the family [[Sabellidae]].\n|\n[[File:Glomerula gordialis.jpg|thumb|center|195px|Example of Glomerula specimen]]\n|-\n|}\n\n=== Mollusca ===\n====Bivalvia====\n[[File:Treibholz mit Muscheln.jpg|thumb|300px|left|Bivalves added to a floating driftwood [[Agathoxylon]]]] \n{| class = \"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Genus\n! Species\n! Stratigraphic position\n! Material\n! Notes\n! Images\n|-\n|\n[[Meleagrinella]]<ref name=\"M\u00fcnsterClamA\">M\u00fcnster, R. G. (1831). Petrefacta Germaniae. In, Arnz & Co, 252.</ref><ref name=\"M\u00fcnsterClamB\">M\u00dcNSTER, G. (1831). GRAF ZU (1831): \u00dcber das geognostische Vorkommen der Ammoneen in Deutschland. Jahrbuch f\u00fcr Mineralogie, Geognosie, Geologie und Petrefaktenkunde, 367-375.</ref><ref name=\"AgassizClamA\">Agassiz, L. (1840). \u00c9tudes critiques sur les mollusques fossiles. L'auteur.</ref>\n|\n*''Meleagrinella substriata''\n|\n* All the Formation<ref name=\"CaswellClamA\">Caswell, B. A., Coe, A. L., & Cohen, A. S. (2009). New range data for marine invertebrate species across the early Toarcian (Early Jurassic) mass extinction. Journal of the Geological Society, 166(5), 859\u2013872.</ref>\n|\nThousands of Specimens.\n|\nA [[Oxytomidae]] [[Scallop]].\n|\n[[File:Meleagrinella substriata 65.jpg|thumb|center|195px|Colony of specimens]]\n|-\n|\n[[Bositra]]<ref name=\"RoemerClamA\">Roemer, F. A. (1836). Die Versteinerungen des Nord-deutschen Oolithen-Gebirges, von Friedrich Adolph Roemer,... Hahn.</ref><ref name=\"M\u00fcnsterClamA\"/><ref name=\"M\u00fcnsterClamB\"/><ref name=\"CaswellClamA\"/><ref name=\"RoemerClamA\"/><ref name=\"AgassizClamA\"/>\n|\n*''Bositra buchii''\n|\n* All the Formation\n|\nThousands of Specimens. \n|\nA \"[[Posidoniidae]]\" [[Ostreoida]]n. Is the type fossil of the Posidonia Shale. In fact, the layers have their name fue to it. Originally was named \"Posidonia bronni\", through to be a new genus, and the strata was denominated the Posidonia layers after it. Years after turns out to be a junior synonym of Bositra, and thus, it was reassigned. Altrought, the name of the layers was left.\n|\n[[File:Bositra buchi.JPG|thumb|center|195px|Thousands of specimens in one matrix]]\n|-\n|\n[[Steinmannia]]<ref name=\"M\u00fcnsterClamA\"/><ref name=\"M\u00fcnsterClamB\"/><ref name=\"AgassizClamA\"/>\n|\n*''Steinmannia bronni''\n*''Steinmannia radiata''\n|\n* All the Formation\n|\nThousands of Specimens. \n|\nA \"[[Posidoniidae]]\" [[Ostreoida]]n. Annother Genera mistaken with \"Posidonia bronni\".\n|\n[[File:Steinmannia bronni.jpg|thumb|center|195px|Various specimens in one matrix]]\n|-\n|\n[[Pseudomytiloides]]<ref name=\"M\u00fcnsterClamA\"/><ref name=\"M\u00fcnsterClamB\"/><ref name=\"CaswellClamA\"/><ref name=\"RoemerClamA\"/><ref name=\"AgassizClamA\"/>\n|\n*''Pseudomytiloides dubius''\n|\n* All the Formation\n|\nThousands of Specimens.\n|\nA [[Inoceramidae]] [[Clam]].\n|\n[[File:Pseudomytiloides dubius.jpg|thumb|center|195px|Single specimen]]\n|-\n|\n[[Nicaniella]]<ref name=\"M\u00fcnsterClamA\"/><ref name=\"M\u00fcnsterClamB\"/><ref name=\"CaswellClamA\"/><ref name=\"RoemerClamA\"/><ref name=\"AgassizClamA\"/>\n|\n*''Nicaniella (Nicaniella) pumila''\n*''Nicaniella striatosulcata''\n\n|\n* All the Formation\n|\nThousands of Specimens.\n|\nA [[Astartidae]] [[Clam]].\n|\n|-\n|\n[[Palaeonucula]]<ref name=\"M\u00fcnsterClamA\"/><ref name=\"M\u00fcnsterClamB\"/><ref name=\"CaswellClamA\"/><ref name=\"RoemerClamA\"/><ref name=\"AgassizClamA\"/>\n|\n*''Palaeonucula ungulella''\n|\n* All the Formation\n|\nThousands of Specimens.\n|\nA [[Nuculidae]] Nut [[Clam]].\n|\n|-\n|\n[[Goniomya]]<ref name=\"M\u00fcnsterClamA\"/><ref name=\"M\u00fcnsterClamB\"/><ref name=\"CaswellClamA\"/><ref name=\"RoemerClamA\"/><ref name=\"AgassizClamA\"/>\n|\n*''Goniomya rhombifera''\n|\n* All the Formation\n|\nThousands of Specimens.\n|\nA [[Pholadomyidae]] [[Clam]].\n|\n|-\n|\n[[Chlamys]]<ref name=\"M\u00fcnsterClamA\"/><ref name=\"M\u00fcnsterClamB\"/><ref name=\"CaswellClamA\"/><ref name=\"RoemerClamA\"/><ref name=\"AgassizClamA\"/>\n|\n*''Chlamys textoria''\n|\n* All the Formation\n|\nThousands of Specimens.\n|\nA [[Pectinoidae]] [[Scallop]].\n|\n[[File:Chlamys varia 20191231.jpg|thumb|center|195px|Single specimen]]\n|-\n|\n[[Pleuromya]]<ref name=\"M\u00fcnsterClamA\"/><ref name=\"M\u00fcnsterClamB\"/><ref name=\"CaswellClamA\"/><ref name=\"RoemerClamA\"/><ref name=\"AgassizClamA\"/>\n|\n*''Pleuromya costata''\n*''Pleuromya ovata''\n*''Pleuromya unioides''\n*''Pleuromya uniformis''\n|\n* All the Formation\n|\nThousands of Specimens.\n|\nA [[Pleuromyidae]] [[Clam]].\n|\n[[File:Klaffmuschel Pleuromya uniformis.jpg|thumb|center|195px|Pleuromya uniformis, two specimens]]\n|-\n|\n[[Propeamussium]]<ref name=\"M\u00fcnsterClamA\"/><ref name=\"M\u00fcnsterClamB\"/><ref name=\"CaswellClamA\"/><ref name=\"RoemerClamA\"/><ref name=\"AgassizClamA\"/>\n|\n*''Propeamussium nonarium''\n|\n* All the Formation\n|\nThousands of Specimens.\n|\nA [[Propeamussiidae]] mud [[Scallop]].\n|\n[[File:Propeamussium pumilum.jpg|thumb|center|195px|Various specimens on the same rock]]\n|-\n|\n[[Gryphaea]]<ref name=\"M\u00fcnsterClamA\"/><ref name=\"M\u00fcnsterClamB\"/><ref name=\"CaswellClamA\"/><ref name=\"RoemerClamA\"/><ref name=\"AgassizClamA\"/>\n|\n*''Gryphaea arcuata''\n|\n* All the Formation\n|\nThousands of Specimens.\n|\nA [[Gryphaeidae]] mud [[Scallop]].\n|\n[[File:Greifmuschel Gryphea arcuata.jpg|thumb|center|195px|Various specimens]]\n|-\n|}\n\n====Gastropoda====\n{| class = \"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Genus\n! Species\n! Stratigraphic position\n! Material\n! Notes\n! Images\n|-\n|\n[[Coelodiscus]]<ref>Teichert, S., & N\u00fctzel, A. (2015). Early Jurassic anoxia triggered the evolution of the oldest holoplanktonic gastropod Coelodiscus minutus by means of heterochrony. Acta Palaeontologica Polonica, 60(2), 269\u2013276.</ref><ref name=\"AgassizClamA\"/>\n|\n*''Coelodiscus minutus''\n|\n* All the Formation\n|\nThousands of Specimens.\n|\nA [[Coelodiscidae]] sea [[Snail]]. The most common of the sea snails of the Formation, it is also one of the most varied in size terms, with some of the biggest specimens of snail from the Lower Toarcian know. It has been related to large floating driftwood as one of the primary settlers.\n|\n|-\n|\n[[Procerithium]]<ref name=\"M\u00fcnsterClamA\"/><ref name=\"M\u00fcnsterClamB\"/><ref name=\"CaswellClamA\"/><ref name=\"RoemerClamA\"/><ref name=\"AgassizClamA\"/>\n|\n*''Procerithium brandi''\n|\n* All the Formation\n|\nThousands of Specimens.\n|\nA [[Procerithiidae]] sea [[Snail]].\n|\n|-\n|\n[[Toarctocera]]<ref>Gr\u00fcndel, J., N\u00fctzel, A., & Schulbert, C. (2009). Toarctocera (Gastropoda, Aporrhaidae): a new genus from the Jurassic (Toarcian/Aalenian) of South Germany and the early evolutionary history of the family Aporrhaidae. Pal\u00e4ontologische Zeitschrift, 83(4), 533.</ref>\n|\n*''Toarctocera subpunctata''\n|\n* All the Formation\n|\nThousands of Specimens.\n|\nA [[Aporrhaidae]] sea [[Snail]]. Among the latest described from the formation, is  one of the earliest certain aporrhaidae. Characterised by large spines growing at the head of the cunch.\n|\n|-\n|\n[[Cryptaulax (gastropod)|Cryptaulax]]<ref name=\"M\u00fcnsterClamA\"/><ref name=\"M\u00fcnsterClamB\"/><ref name=\"CaswellClamA\"/><ref name=\"RoemerClamA\"/><ref name=\"AgassizClamA\"/>\n|\n*''Cryptaulax armatum''\n|\n* All the Formation\n|\nThousands of Specimens.\n|\nA [[Cryptaulacidae]] sea [[Snail]].\n|\n|-\n|\n[[Neritaria]]<ref name=\"M\u00fcnsterClamA\"/><ref name=\"M\u00fcnsterClamB\"/><ref name=\