 An intact comatulid crinoid from the Toarcian of Southern Germany. Stuttgarter Beitr\u00e4ge zur Naturkunde Serie B (Geologie und Pal\u00e4ontologie) 140:1-7</ref>\n|\n*''Ophiopholis trispinosa'' \n|\n* Holzmaden\n|\nFew Specimens.\n|\nA brittle star. Very rare on the layers.\n|\n[[File:Bulletin (1904-) (20395173566).jpg|thumb|center|155px|Modern Specimen]]\n|-\n|\n[[Mesophiomusium]]<ref name=\"SeaStars\"/>\n|\n*''Mesophiomusium geisingense''<ref>M. Kutscher. 1992. Ophiomusium geisingense n.sp. eine neue Ophiurenart aus dem Lias Epsilon (Unteres Toarcium) von Bachhausen/Bayern. Archaeopteryx 10:25-30</ref> \n*''Mesophiomusium scabrum'' \n|\n* Holzmaden\n|\nFew Specimens.\n|\nA brittle star. Mesophiomusium geisingense is the most common of the two.\n|\n|-\n|\n[[Ophiarachna]]<ref name=\"SeaStars\"/>\n|\n*''Ophiarachna liasica''  \n|\n* Holzmaden\n|\nVarious Specimens.\n|\nA brittle star. Very Common.\n|\n|-\n|\n[[Sinosura]]<ref name=\"SeaStars\"/><ref name=\"H. Hess 1991\">H. Hess. 1991. Neue Schlangensterne aus dem Toarcium und Aalenium des Schw\u00e4bischen Jura (Baden-W\u00fcrttemberg). Stuttgarter Beitr\u00e4ge zur Naturkunde, serie B, Geologie und Pal\u00e4ontologie 180:1-11</ref>\n|\n*''Sinosura brodiei''  \n|\n* Holzmaden\n|\nVarious Specimens.\n|\nA brittle star. Very Common.\n|\n[[File:Sinosura kelheimense (Boehm, 1889) 90.3.9802.jpg|thumb|center|155px|Fossil Specimen]]\n|-\n|style=\"background:#E6E6E6;\"|\n?[[Ophiura]]<ref name=\"SeaStars\"/>\n|style=\"background:#E6E6E6;\"|\n*''Ophiura astonensis''  \n|style=\"background:#E6E6E6;\"|\n* Holzmaden\n|style=\"background:#E6E6E6;\"|\nFew Specimens.\n|style=\"background:#E6E6E6;\"|\nA brittle star. Very Rare.\n|style=\"background:#E6E6E6;\"|\n[[File:Ophiura.png|thumb|center|155px|Appearance]]\n|-\n|style=\"background:#E6E6E6;\"|\n?[[Ophiocten]]<ref name=\"SeaStars\"/>\n|style=\"background:#E6E6E6;\"|\n*''Ophiocten seeweni''  \n|style=\"background:#E6E6E6;\"|\n* Holzmaden\n|style=\"background:#E6E6E6;\"|\nFew Specimens.\n|style=\"background:#E6E6E6;\"|\nA brittle star. Rare.\n|style=\"background:#E6E6E6;\"|\n|-\n|style=\"background:#E6E6E6;\"|\n?[[Pentasteria]]<ref name=\"SeaStars\"/>\n|style=\"background:#E6E6E6;\"|\n*''Pentasteria sp.''  \n|style=\"background:#E6E6E6;\"|\n* Banz\n|style=\"background:#E6E6E6;\"|\nFew Specimens.\n|style=\"background:#E6E6E6;\"|\nA sea star of the family [[Astropectinidae]]. Rare.\n|style=\"background:#E6E6E6;\"|\n[[File:Seestern Pentasteria sp.jpg|thumb|center|155px|Pentasteria sp. from Banz]]\n|-\n|}\n\n====Echinoidea====\n{| class = \"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Genus\n! Species\n! Stratigraphic position\n! Material\n! Notes\n! Images\n|-\n|\n[[Cidaris]]<ref name=\"Urchin\">Gall, J. C. (1983). The Holzmaden Bituminous Shale Sea. In Ancient Sedimentary Environments and the Habitats of Living Organisms (pp. 158-166). Springer, Berlin, Heidelberg.</ref>\n|\n*''Cidaris sp.'' \n|\n* Holzmaden\n|\nFew Specimens.\n|\nA sea urchin. Common on several layers. Cidaris is genus that still alive today. A bottom dweller, is commonly found associated with Belemnnite fossils, probably due to eating its carcasses.\n|\n[[File:Cidaris cidaris MHNT.jpg|thumb|center|155px|Modern Specimen]]\n|-\n|\n[[Diademopsis]]<ref name=\"Riegraf1\"/>\n|\n*''Diademopsis crinifera''\n*''Diademopsis sp.'' \n|\n* Holzmaden\n* Ohmden\n* Altforf\n* Banz\n* Regensburg\n|\nDocens of Specimens\n|\nA sea urchin of the family [[Pedinidae]]. It is the most common sea urchin in the formation, present on all the levels with specimens of various sizes. Vinculated to sea bottom sediments, before Gasteropods and Bivalves, Diademospsis was the tird major colonizer of the bottom, in between anoxic changes.\n|\n[[File:Diademopsis crinifera.JPG|thumb|center|155px|Specimens from Holzmaden]]\n|-\n|\n[[Procidaris]]<ref name=\"Riegraf1\"/>\n|\n*''Procidaris sp.''\n|\n* Holzmaden\n* Banz\n* Regensburg\n|\nFew Specimens.\n|\nA sea urchin of the family [[Miocidaridae]]\n|\n|-\n|}\n\n====Holothuroidea====\n{| class = \"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Genus\n! Species\n! Stratigraphic position\n! Material\n! Notes\n! Images\n|-\n|\n[[Uncinulina]]<ref name=\"Holo\">H. Mostler. 1972. Holothuriensklerite aus dem Jura der N\u00f6rdlischen Kalkalpen und S\u00fcdtiroler Dolomiten. Geologisch-Pal\u00e4ontologische Mitteilungen Innsbruck 2(6):1-29</ref>\n|\n*''Uncinulina parvispinosa'' \n|\n* Maurach\n|\nFew Specimens.\n|\nA Sea Cucumber of the Family [[Elasipodida]]. Common on the Austrian realm, characterised due to been present of Pelagic environments, as is common on modern genera of its family, but not on the fossil record. Can be the oldest pelagic representative of the Sea Cucumber family. Can be also related to the modern deep sea genus [[Enypniastes]].\n|\n[[File:Enypniastes eximia Puerto Rico.jpg|thumb|center|155px|Modern Species Enypniastes can be related to Uncinulina]]\n|-\n|}\n\n====Crinoidea====\n{| class = \"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Genus\n! Species\n! Stratigraphic position\n! Material\n! Notes\n! Images\n|-\n|\n[[Procomaster]]<ref name=\"SeaStars\"/>\n|\n*''Procomaster pentadactylus''\n|\n* Holzmaden\n|\nMultiple specimens.\n|\nA comatulid crinoid.\n|\n|-\n|\n[[Praetetracrinus]]<ref name=\"Crino1\">M. J\u00e4ger. 1995. Echinodermata aus dem Ober-Toarcium und Aalenium Deutschlands I. Crinoidea: Cyrtocrinina und Millericrinina. Stuttgarter Beitr\u00e4ge zur Naturkunde Serie B (Geologie und Pal\u00e4ontologie) 226:1-51</ref>\n|\n*''Praetetracrinus kutscheri''\n|\n* Holzmaden\n|\nMultiple specimens.\n|\nA Plicatocrinid crinoid.\n|\n|-\n|\n[[Shroshaecrinus]]<ref name=\"Crino1\"/>\n|\n*''?Shroshaecrinus quedlinburgensis''\n|\n* Holzmaden\n|\nMultiple specimens.\n|\nA Millericrinid crinoid.\n|\n|-\n|\n[[Isocrinus]]<ref>Miller, J. S. (1821). A Natural History of the Crinoidea, Or Lily-shaped Animals; with Observations on the Genera, Asteria, Euryale. Comatula Et Marsupites. Frost.</ref>\n|\n*''Isocrinus basaltiformis''\n|\n* Holzmaden\n* Banz\n|\nMultiple specimens.\n|\nA Isocrinidae crinoid.\n|\n[[File:Seelilie Isocrinus basaltiformis, Stiel mit Kelch.jpg|thumb|center|225px|Close view of one specimen]]\n[[File:Seelilie Isocrinus basaltiformis, fein verzweigte Fangarme.jpg|thumb|center|155px|Single specimen]]\n|-\n|\n[[Seirocrinus]]<ref name=\"Crino0\"/>\n|\n*''Seirocrinus subangularis''\n|\n* Nearly All the Formation\n|\nMultiple specimens. Fossilized rafts of +10 m long with complete colonies.\n|\nAmong the tallest animals of its period, Seirocrinus is also one of the most famous fossils from the Posidonia Shale. It consists of fossils of colonies along large wood trunks, with specimens up to 14 m long, with the largest specimen reaching 26 m long,<ref>Simms 1989.Contrasting lifestyles in lower Jurassic crinoids: A comparision of benthic and pseudopelagic Isocrinida. Palaeontology. 29: 475-493.</ref> what makes it among the tallest know Mesozoic organisms, one of the largest invertebrates know on the fossil record and one of the tallest know animals. It was an open ocean organism that lived in rafting woods, probably filtering food and serving as a refuge for other animals, such as ammonites.<ref>Seilacher, A., Drozdzewski, G., & Haude, R. (1968). Form and function of the stem in a pseudoplanktonic crinoid (Seirocrinus). Palaeontology, 11(2), 275-282.</ref> The crinoids had a large colonization process, based on the status of the fossil wood found.<ref>Haude, R., & Jangoux, M. (1980, June). Constructional morphology of the stems of Pentacrinitidae, and mode of life of Seirocrinus. In Proceedings of the European Colloquium on Echinoderms, Brussels. AA Balkema, Rotterdam (pp. 17-23).</ref><ref>Hagdorn, H. (2016). From benthic to pseudoplanktonic life: morphological remodeling of the Triassic crinoid Traumatocrinus and the Jurassic Seirocrinus during habitat change. PalZ, 90(2), 225-241.</ref> The large rafts where the home for a high variety of marine organisms, such as Balanoideans, Ammonites and other. It has been stimated that without the presence of modern raft wood predators (that apperared on the [[Bathonian]]) those rafts can last up to 5 years, being that the main reason the crinoids where able to attach such huge sizes. The large rafts where also proabaly essential to distribute animals along the Early Jurassic Seas.<ref>Hunter, A. W., Mitchell, E. G., Casenove, D., & Mayers, C. (2019). Reconstructing the ecology of a Jurassic pseudoplanktonic megaraft colony. bioRxiv, 566844.</ref>\n|\n[[File:Seirocrinus subangularis (fossil crinoid) (Posidonia Shale, Lower Jurassic; Holzmaden area, Germany) 1 (35674916591).jpg|thumb|center|225px|Close view of one specimen]]\n[[File:Seirocrinus subangularis 3334.jpg|thumb|center|155px|Single specimen]]\n|-\n|\n[[Pentacrinites]]<ref>Rasmussen, H. W. (1977). Function and attachment of the stem in Isocrinidae and Pentacrinitidae: review and interpretation. Lethaia, 10(1), 51-57.</ref>\n|\n*''Pentacrinites fossilis'' \n*''Pentacrinites briareus''\n*''Pentacrinites dichotomus''\n*''Pentacrinites quenstedti''<ref>R. B. Hauff. 1984. Pentacrinites quenstedti (Oppel) aus dem oberen Untertoarcium (Lias Epsilon) von Ohmden bei Holzmaden (SW-Deutschland). Palaeontologische Zeitschrift 58:255-263</ref> \n|\n* Holzmaden\n* Bavaria\n* Banz\n|\nMultiple specimens. Fossilized rafts of +10 m long with complete colonies.\n|\nLike Seirocrinus, Pentacrinites formed colonies on rafting wood, getting a different role than bigger crinoid and appearing on the first stages of the descomposition of the rafting wood. Was an smaller genus, with specimens of no more than 1 meter long, usually measuring 40\u201370&nbsp;cm.\n|\n[[File:Pentacrinites dichotomus.JPG|thumb|center|225px|Close view of one specimen]]\n[[File:Pentacrinites NT.jpg|thumb|center|205px|Reconstruction]]\n|-\n|}\n\n==Vertebrata==\n=== Fishes ===\n====Chondrichthyes====\n{| class = \"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Genus\n! Species\n! Stratigraphic position\n! Material\n! Notes\n! Images\n|-\n|\n[[Crassodus]]<ref>M. W. Maisch and A. T. Matzke. 2016. A new hybodontid shark (Chondrichthyes, Hybodontiformes) from the Lower Jurassic Posidonienschiefer Formation of Dotternhausen, SW Germany. Neues Jahrbuch f\u00fcr Geologie und Pal\u00e4ontologie, Abhandlungen 280:241-257</ref>\n|\n*''Crassodus reifi''\n|\n* Holzmaden\n|\nMultiple specimens.\n|\nA shark of the family [[Hybodontidae]].\n|\n|-\n|\n[[Microtoxodus]]<ref name=\"Delsate\">D. Delsate. 2003. Une nouvelle faune des poissons et requins Toarciens du sud du Luxembourg (Dudelange) et de L'Allemange (Sch\u00f6mberg). Bulletin de l'Acad\u00e9mie Lorrain des Sciences 42:13-49</ref>\n|\n*''Microtoxodus gulakmani''<ref name=\"Delsate\"/>\n|\n* Sch\u00f6mberg, W\u00fcrttemberg \n|\nMultiple specimens.\n|\nA non classified [[Elasmobranch]].\n|\n|-\n|\n[[Protospinax]]<ref name=\"Delsate\"/><ref name=\"DelsateLuxem\"/>\n|\n*''Protospinax sp.''\n|\n* Sch\u00f6mberg, W\u00fcrttemberg\n* Dudelange-Zoufftgen\n|\nMultiple specimens.\n|\nA member of the family [[Protospinacidae]].\n|\n|-\n|style=\"background:#E6E6E6;\"|\n[[Mesiteia]]<ref name=\"Delsate\"/>\n|style=\"background:#E6E6E6;\"|\n*''? Mesiteia sp.''\n|style=\"background:#E6E6E6;\"|\n* Sch\u00f6mberg, W\u00fcrttemberg\n* Dudelange-Zoufftgen\n|style=\"background:#E6E6E6;\"|\nMultiple specimens.\n|style=\"background:#E6E6E6;\"|\nA [[Carpet Shark]] of the family [[Orectolobiformes]].\n|style=\"background:#E6E6E6;\"|\n|-\n|style=\"background:#E6E6E6;\"|\n[[Chiloscyllium]]<ref name=\"Delsate\"/>\n|style=\"background:#E6E6E6;\"|\n*''? Chiloscyllium sp.''\n|style=\"background:#E6E6E6;\"|\n* Sch\u00f6mberg, W\u00fcrttemberg\n* Dudelange-Zoufftgen\n|style=\"background:#E6E6E6;\"|\nMultiple specimens.\n|style=\"background:#E6E6E6;\"|\nA [[Carpet Shark]] of the family [[Hemiscylliidae]].\n|style=\"background:#E6E6E6;\"|\n[[File:Chiloscyllium plagiosum2.jpg|thumb|center|195px|Modern ''[[Chiloscyllium]]'']]\n|-\n|\n[[Palaeobrachaelurus]]<ref name=\"Delsate\"/><ref name=\"DelsateLuxem\"/>\n|\n*''Palaeobrachaelurus sp. ''\n|