an modern Tuatara.<ref>Klein, N.; Scheyer, T.M. (2017). \"Microanatomy and life history in Palaeopleurosaurus (Rhynchocephalia: Pleurosauridae) from the Early Jurassic of Germany\". The Science of Nature. 104 (4): 4. doi:10.1007/s00114-016-1427-3. {{PMID|28005148}}.</ref>\n|\n[[File:Palaeopleurosaurus model.jpg|thumb|center|125px|''[[Palaeopleurosaurus]]'']]\n|-\n|}\n\n==== Testudinata ====\n{| class = \"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Genus\n! Species\n! Stratigraphic position\n! Material\n! Notes\n! Images\n|-\n|\n[[Testudinata]]<ref>M\u00fcnster, G. (1834): Briefl. Mitteilung. - N.Jb.Min., S. 42 - 43</ref><ref>M\u00dcNSTER, G.G. ZU. 1834. Mittheilung, an Professor Bronn\ngerichtet. Neues Jahrbuch f\u00fcr Mineralogie, Geognosie, Geologie und Petrefaktenkunde 1834:42\u201343.</ref><ref>Schleich, H. H. (1984). Ein neuer Schildkr\u00f6tennachweis aus Lias-Sedimenten Deutschlands. Naturwissenschaftliche Zeitschrift f\u00fcr Niederbayern, 30, 56\u201362.</ref>\n|\n*''Testudinata indeterminate A''\n*''Testudinata indeterminate B''\n*''Testudinata indeterminate C''\n|\n* Altdorf, Bavaria\n|\nVarious partial specimens, mostly pleurals.\n|\nUnclassified Testudine. M\u00fcnster (1834) cited: \" there were also rare things at the quarries of Altdorf, among other remains there where ones of a turtle on lias limestone\"\". The remains are not cataloged.<ref name=\"Turtle\">Joyce, W. G. (2017). A review of the fossil record of basal Mesozoic turtles. Bulletin of the Peabody Museum of Natural History, 58(1), 65\u2013113.</ref>\n|\n|-\n|style=\"background:#E6E6E6;\"|\n[[Mesochelydia]]?<ref>THEODORI, L. 1831. \u00dcber die Knochen vom Genus Pterodactylus aus der Lias-Formation in der Gegend von Banz. Isis von\nOken 1831:276\u2013281.</ref>\n|style=\"background:#E6E6E6;\"|\n*''Mesochelydia? indeterminate A''\n*''Mesochelydia? indeterminate B''\n|style=\"background:#E6E6E6;\"|\n* Banz, Bavaria\n|style=\"background:#E6E6E6;\"|\nVarious partial specimens, mostly pleurals. Includes a left partial shell.\n|style=\"background:#E6E6E6;\"|\nAssigned to Mesochelydia(?) due to resemblances for the authors to modern turtles. Unclassified and non cataloged.<ref name=\"Turtle\"/>\n|style=\"background:#E6E6E6;\"|\n|-\n|style=\"background:#E6E6E6;\"|\n[[Perichelydia]]?<ref name=\"TerrestrialFrags\">Joger, U., Kosma, R., Zellmer, H., & R\u00f6hling, H. G. (2018). Saurier im Braunschweiger Land. Die Fund-und Grabungsstellen von Hondelage und Schandelah (Unterjura, Posidonienschiefer) sowie des Langenberg bei Goslar/Oker (Oberjura, Malm)(Exkursion N am 7. April 2018). Jahresberichte und Mitteilungen des Oberrheinischen Geologischen Vereins, 447\u2013479.</ref>\n|style=\"background:#E6E6E6;\"|\n*''Perichelydia? indeterminate A''\n|style=\"background:#E6E6E6;\"|\n* Schandelah\n|style=\"background:#E6E6E6;\"|\nFragmentary Remains\n|style=\"background:#E6E6E6;\"|\nCan be a more basal taxon or even not a turtle. If it is, can be the first Turtle remains found on the Posidonia Shale since the late 1800s. Now on a private collection.<ref name=\"TerrestrialFrags\"/>\n|style=\"background:#E6E6E6;\"|\n|-\n|}\n\n==== Crocodrylomorpha ====\n{| class = \"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Genus\n! Species\n! Stratigraphic position\n! Material\n! Notes\n! Images\n|-\n|\n[[Steneosaurus]]<ref name=\"F. Westphal 1962\">F. Westphal. 1962. Die Krokodilier des Deutschen und Englischen Oberen Lias [The crocodiles of the German and English Upper Lias]. Palaeontographica Abteilung A 118(1-3):23\u2013118</ref>\n|\n*''Steneosaurus bollensis''\n|\n* Banz\n* Altdorf\n* Schandelah\n* Niedersachsen\n* Holzmaden\n* Regensburg\n|\nComplete specimens.\n|\nA marine crocodrylomorph with a diet probably based on fish.<ref>Mueller-T\u00f6we, I. J. (2006). Feeding options in Steneosaurus bollensis (Mesoeucrocodylia. Thalattosuchia). Hantkeniana Spec, 5, 46\u201348.</ref> It is the best known member of the family Teleosauriade.\n|\n[[File:Macrospondylus bollensis Holzmaden.jpg|thumb|center|125px|''[[Steneosaurus]]'']]\n|-\n|\n[[Mystriosaurus]]<ref>Kaup, J.J. 1841. \u00dcber Mystriosaurus-Reste aus dem Lias-Kalk von Altdorf. In: G. Bronn and J.J. Kaup (eds.), Abhandlungen \u00fcber die gavial-artigen Reptilien der Lias-Formation. 47 pp. E. Schweizerbart\u2018sche Verlagshandlung, Stuttgart.</ref><ref>Winkler, T. C. (1876). Etude sur le genre mystriosaurus et description de deux exemplaires nouveaux de ce genre (Vol. 1).</ref>\n|\n*''Mystriosaurus laurillardi''\n|\n* Banz\n* Altdorf\n* Holzmaden\n|\nComplete specimen.\n|\nA marine crocodrylomorph with a diet probably based on fish. Was considered synonymous with [[Steneosaurus]] until recently.<ref>Sachs, S.; Johnson, M.M.; Young, M.T.; Abel, P. (2019). \"The mystery of Mystriosaurus: Redescribing the poorly known Early Jurassic teleosauroid thalattosuchians Mystriosaurus laurillardi and Steneosaurus brevior\" (PDF). Acta Palaeontologica Polonica. 64 (3): 565\u2013579. doi:10.4202/app.00557.2018.</ref>\n|\n[[File:Palais de Rumine (Lausanne)-05.JPG|thumb|center|125px|''[[Mystriosaurus]]'']]\n|-\n|\n[[Platysuchus]]<ref>B E R CK H E ME R , F. 1929. Beitrag zur Kenntnis der Krokodilier des schwa\u00a8bischen oberen Lias.Neues Jahrbuch fu\u00a8r Mineralogie, Geologie und Pala\u00a8ontologie, Abteilung B,64, 1\u201360.</ref>\n|\n*''Platysuchus multiscrobiculatus''\n|\n* Banz\n* Altdorf\n* Schandelah\n* Niedersachsen\n* Holzmaden\n* Regensburg\n|\nComplete specimen.\n|\nA marine crocodrylomorph with a diet probably based on fish.\n|\n[[File:Platysuchus multiscrobiculatus 1.JPG|thumb|center|125px|''[[Platysuchus]]'']]\n|-\n|\n[[Pelagosaurus]]<ref>Bronn HG. 1841. \u00dcber die fossilen Gaviale der Lias-Formation und der Oolithe. Archiv f\u00fcr Naturgeschichte, Berlin 8:77\u201382.</ref><ref>Pierce, S. E., & Benton, M. J. (2006). Pelagosaurus typus Bronn, 1841 (Mesoeucrocodylia: Thalattosuchia) from the Upper Lias (Toarcian, Lower Jurassic) of Somerset, England. Journal of Vertebrate Paleontology, 26(3), 621\u2013635.</ref>\n|\n*''Pelagosaurus typus''\n|\n* Banz\n* Altdorf\n* Holzmaden\n|\nComplete specimen.\n|\nA marine crocodrylomorph with a diet probably based on fish (one fossil specimen was found with a [[Leptolepis]] in its stomach contents). Has been considered a basal Metriorhynchidae<ref>Buffetaut, E. (1980). Position syst\u00e9matique et phylog\u00e9n\u00e9tique du genre Pelagosaurus Bronn, 1841 (Crocodylia, Mesosuchia), du Toarcien d'Europe. Geobios, 13(5), 783\u2013786.</ref> or sister taxon to both Teleosauridae and Metriorhynchidae.<ref>Benton MJ, Clark JM. 1988. Archosaur phylogeny and the relationships of the Crocodylia; pp. 295\u2013338 in MJ. Benton (ed.), The phylogeny and classification of the tetrapods, Vol. 1. Amphibians, Reptiles, Birds. Systematic Association Special Volume 35A. Clarendon Press, Oxford.</ref>\n|\n[[File:Pelagosaurus typus.JPG|thumb|center|125px|''[[Pelagosaurus]]'']]\n|-\n|style=\"background:#E6E6E6;\"|\n[[Pholidosauridae]]?<ref name=\"F. Westphal 1962\"/>\n|style=\"background:#E6E6E6;\"|\n*''Indeterminate''\n|style=\"background:#E6E6E6;\"|\n* Holzheim bei G\u00f6ppingen\n|style=\"background:#E6E6E6;\"|\nPartial specimen.\n|style=\"background:#E6E6E6;\"|\nA marine crocodrylomorph. Can be a mistaken Teleosaurian. Has been included on Cf. Platysuchus, altrougth has characters that align it with [[Anglosuchus]], that was also confused with a Teleosaurid.\n|style=\"background:#E6E6E6;\"|\n|-\n|style=\"background:#E6E6E6;\"|\n[[Protosuchidae]]?<ref name=\"TerrestrialFrags\"/>\n|style=\"background:#E6E6E6;\"|\n*''Indeterminate''\n|style=\"background:#E6E6E6;\"|\n* Schandelah\n|style=\"background:#E6E6E6;\"|\nFragmentary remains\n|style=\"background:#E6E6E6;\"|\nA terrestrial, maybe semi-acuatic crocodrylomorph. Can be a mistaken juvenile Teleosaurian.\n|style=\"background:#E6E6E6;\"|\n|-\n|}\n\n==== Pterosaurs ====\n{| class = \"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Genus\n! Species\n! Stratigraphic position\n! Material\n! Notes\n! Images\n|-\n|\n[[Campylognathoides]]<ref>Plieninger, F. (1894). \"Campylognathus Zittelli. Ein neuer Flugsaurier aus dem Oberen Lias Schwabens\", Palaeontographica, 41: 193-222</ref><ref>Wellnhofer, P. (1974). Campylognathoides liasicus (Quenstedt), an Upper Liassic pterosaur from Holzmaden. The Pittsburgh Specimen.</ref><ref name=\"jurptersum\">Wellnhofer, Peter (1991). \"Summary of Lower Jurassic Pterosaurs.\" ''The Illustrated Encyclopedia of Pterosaurs.'' London, UK: Salamander Books Limited. p. 79. {{ISBN|0-86101-566-5}}.</ref>\n|\n*''Campylognathoides zitteli''<ref name=\"jurptersum\" />\n*''Campylognathoides liasicus''<ref name=\"jurptersum\" />\n|\n* Banz\n* Altdorf\n* Schandelah\n* Niedersachsen\n* Holzmaden\n|\nSeveral specimens with different degrees of preservation.\n|\nA [[Novialoidea]]n Pterosaur, type genus of the family [[Campylognathoidea]]. Mark Witton suggests the construction of Campylognathoides' extremely robust forelimbs, with proportionally long wing fingers, could be a specialization for a fast aerial lifestyle comparable to those of [[Falcons]] and [[Mastiff bat (disambiguation)|mastiff bat]]s, being more probably an insect & vertebrate hunter and living on nearshore environments.<ref>Witton, Mark P. (2013), Pterosaurs: Natural History, Evolution, Anatomy</ref> \n|\n[[File:Campylogn DB.jpg|thumb|center|125px|''[[Campylognathoides]]'']]\n[[File:Campylognthoides.JPG|thumb|center|125px|Nearly complete ''[[Campylognathoides]]'']]\n|-\n|\n[[Novialoidea]]<ref>Wellnhofer, P. & Vahldiek, B.-W. (1986). \"Ein Flugsaurier-Rest aus dem Posidonienschiefer (Unter-Toarcium) von Schandelah bei Braunschweig\", Pal\u00e4ontologische Zeitschrift, 60: 329\u2013340</ref>\n|\n*''Indeterminate''\n|\n*Schandelah\n|\nPelvis and several vertebrae.\n|\nA [[Novialoidea]]n Pterosaur. Has been assigned to the genus [[Campylognathoides]], although it is clearly different than any other pterosaur from the Posidonia Shale.\n|\n|-\n|\n[[Parapsicephalus]]<ref>O'Sullivan, M.; Martill, D.M. (2017). \"The taxonomy and systematics of Parapsicephalus purdoni (Reptilia: Pterosauria) from the Lower Jurassic Whitby Mudstone Formation, Whitby, U.K\". Historical Biology. 29 (8): 1009\u20131018. doi:10.1080/08912963.2017.1281919</ref>\n|\n*''cf. Parapsicephalus purdoni''\n|\n*Altdorf\n|\nSkull\n|\nA [[Rhamphorhynchinae]] Pterosaur. Has been assigned to the genus [[Dorygnathus]]. It has a really complete skull that can help to explain the estatus of the genus Parapsicephalus.\n|\n|-\n|\n[[Dorygnathus]]<ref>Padian, K. (2008). The Early Jurassic pterosaur Dorygnathus banthensis (Theodori, 1830). EARLY JURASSIC PTEROSAUR DORYGNATHUS BANTHENSIS (THEODORI, 1830), (80), 69\u2013107.</ref><ref>Wiman, C. (1923). \u00fcber Dorygnathus und andere Flugsaurier. Bulletin of the Geological Institute of Upsala, 19, 23\u201355.</ref>\n|\n*''Dorygnathus banthensis''<ref>Broili, F. (1939). Ein Dorygnathus mit Hautresten. Verlagd. Bayer. Akad. d. Wiss..</ref>\n*''Dorygnathus mistelgauensis?''<ref>R. Wild. 1971. Dorygnathus mistelgauensis n. sp., ein neuer Flugsaurier aus dem Lias Epsilon von Mistelgau (Fr\u00e4nkischer Jura). Geologische Bl\u00e4tter f\u00fcr Nordost-Bayern und angrenzende Gebiete 21(4):178\u2013195</ref>\n|\n* Banz\n* Altdorf\n* Schandelah\n* Niedersachsen\n* Holzmaden\n|\nMultiple specimens with different degree of preservation.<ref>Arthaber, G. (1921). Studien \u00fcder Flugsaurier auf Grund der Bearbeitung des Wiener Examplares von Dorygnathus banthensis. Denkschr. Akad. Wien, Bd. XCVII.(with the list of extensive literature on Pterosauria).</ref> \n|\nA [[Rhamphorhynchinae]] Pterosaur. It is one of the best known Early Jurassic Pterosaurs. Unlike Campylognthoides, Dorygnathus was an oceanic hunter, with teeth disposed to catch marine prey, such as Belemnittes and several species of fishes. Dorygnathus mistelgauensis is considered a junior synonym until more data can be recovered from the specimen, held on a private collection.\n|\n[[File:Terrestrial Dorygnathus.png|thumb|center|125px|''[[Dorygnathus]]'' on terrestrial pose]]\n[[File:Dorygnathus banthensis.jpg|thumb|center|125px|Nearly complete ''[[Dorygnathus]]'']]\n|-\n|}\n\n==== Sauropoda ====\n{| class = \"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Genus\n! Species\n! Stratigraphic position\n! Material\n! Notes\n! Images\n|-\n|\n[[Ohmdenosaurus]]<ref>Wild, R. (1978). \"Ein Sauropoden-Rest (Reptilia, Saurischia) aus dem Posidonienschiefer (Lias, Toarcium) von Holzmaden\". Stuttgarter Beitr\u00e4ge zur Naturkunde, Serie B (Geologie und Pal\u00e4ontologie) (in German). 41: 1\u201315.</ref>\n|\n*''Ohmdenosaurus liasicus''\n|\n* Holzmaden\n|\nTibia and astragalus\n|\nA [[Gravisauria]]n Sauropod. One of the few formally described from the Toarcian. Has been related with [[Vulcanodon]], although more recent studies placed it as a relative of [[Rhoetosaurus]].<ref>Nair, J. P., & Salisbury, S. W. (2012). New anatomical information on Rhoetosaurus brownei Longman, 1926, a gravisaurian sauropodomorph dinosaur from the Middle Jurassic of Queensland, Australia. Journal of Vertebrate Paleontology, 32(2), 369-394</ref> It has been claimed to be a small sauropod with a size of 4 m, altrought the tibia measures 405 to 410&nbsp;mm, leading to a 6.7 m long sauropod. Molina P\u00e9rez & Larramendi, stimated a modern size of 6.2 to 6.7 m long, with a weight of 1.3 tonnes.<ref>RUBEN. LARRAMENDI MOLINA-PEREZ (ASIER.). (2020). DINOSAUR FACTS AND FIGURES: The Sauropods and Other Sauropodomorphs. PRINCETON UNIVERSITY PRES.</ref>\n|\n[[File:Ohmdenosaurus Reconstruction.jpg|thumb|center|225px|''[[Ohmdenosaurus]]'']]\n|-\n|}\n\n==== Synapsida ====\n{| class = \"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Genus\n! Species\n! Stratigraphic position\n! Material\n! Notes\n! Images\n|-\n|style=\"background:#f3e9f3;\" |\n[[Trithelodontidae]]?<ref>M\u00dcNSTER, G. (1836). Letter on various fossils. Neues Jahrbuch f\u00fcr Mineralogie, Geognosie, Geologie und Petrefaktenkunde, 1836, 580\u2013583.</ref>\n|style=\"background:#f3e9f3;\" |\n*''Trithelodontidae? Indeterminate''\n|style=\"background:#f3e9f3;\" |\n* Banz\n|style=\"background:#f3e9f3;\" |\n3 Tooth\n|style=\"background:#f3e9f3;\" |\nThe Specimens were listed on several notes on the 1800s, although its existence has not been proved. Can be related to the Trithelodontidae by related characters, such as [[Irajatherium]] Left maxilla teeth. but that would imply a great gost lineage since the [[Sinemurian]]. If its presence is proved, it would be the first Mammaliform found on the Posidonia Shale.\n|style=\"background:#f3e9f3;\" |\n|-\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{Portal|Geology|Paleontology}}\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110930132528/http://www.urweltmuseum.de/website/museum/index.htm Images of fossils in the Urwelt-Museum Hauff (Holzmaden)]\n\n[[Category:Posidonia Shale| ]]\n[[Category:Paleontology in Germany]]\n[[Category:Prehistoric fauna by locality|Posidonia]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Seironcrinus subangularis Miller, die gr\u00f6\u00dfte fossile Seelilien-Kolonie (18 x 6 m).jpg|thumb|380px|right|18x6 m fossilized floating wood ([[Araucarioxylon]]), with Crinoids attached ([[Pentacrinites]] & [[Seirocrinus]]). It is one of the most emblematic fossils of the formation, where the anoxic seas of the lower toarcian lead to an exquisite preservation.]]\n{{Paleontology}}\nThe [[Posidonia Shale]]  is a [[geological formation]] of southwestern [[Germany]], northern [[Switzerland]], western [[Czech Republic]], northwestern [[Austria]] and the [[Netherlands]], that spans about 3 million years during the [[Early Jurassic]] period (early [[Toarcian]] stage). It is known for its detailed [[fossil]]s, especially sea fauna, listed below.\n\n=== Algae ===\nIncludes abundant variety of algae, such as the genus of colonial Green algae [[Botryococcus]],<ref>Gorbanenko, O. O., & Ligouis, B. (2014). Changes in optical properties of liptinite macerals from early mature to post mature stage in Posidonia Shale (Lower Toarcian, NW Germany). International journal of coal geology, 133, 47-59.</ref> or the unicellular algal bodies [[Tasmanites]], and other small examples. Algae are a good reference for changes on the oxygen conditions along the Toarcian.<ref>Schouten, S., van Kaam-Peters, H. M., Rijpstra, W. I. C., Schoell, M., & Damste, J. S. S. (2000). Effects of an oceanic anoxic event on the stable carbon isotopic composition of early Toarcian carbon. American Journal of Science, 300(1), 1\u201322.</ref>\n\n{{paleobiota-key-compact}}\n\n====Rhodophyta====\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Genus\n! Species\n! Location\n! Stratigraphic position\n! Material\n! Notes\n! Images\n|-\n|style=\"background:#E6E6E6;\"|\n''Cf. [[Rhodophyta]]''<ref>Ruebsam, W., & Schwark, L. (2017). Phytoplankton community dynamics during the Early Toarcian Oceanic Anoxic Event deduced from high-resolution biomarker investigation. In Proceedings of the 1st International Workshop on the Toarcian Oceanic Anoxic Event (IW-TOAE): Impact on Marine Carbon Cycle and Ecosystems, IGCP-655, Ja\u00e9n (pp. 101\u2013102).</ref>\n|style=\"background:#E6E6E6;\"|\n*''Cf. Rhodophyta sp.''\n''\n|style=\"background:#E6E6E6;\"|\n* Banz\n* Holzmaden\n|style=\"background:#E6E6E6;\"|\n|style=\"background:#E6E6E6;\"|\nSeveral Specimens\n|style=\"background:#E6E6E6;\"|\nPossible affinities with [[Rhodophyta]]. Are among the few complete specimens of Algae found on lower Jurassic sediments, being called \"Seegrasblatt\" (Seagrass leaf), have more in common with modern [[Chondria (alga)|Chondria]] dasyphylla, ranging from 25 cm to near 1 m long. Its affinities haven\u00b4t been proved. There are several specimens that resemble the also modern [[Delesseria]] sinuosa.\n|style=\"background:#E6E6E6;\"|\n[[File:Seegrasblatt.jpg|thumb|center|195px|''Seegrasblatt'', possible Cf.Rhodophyta exposed in Banz Abbey]]\n|-\n|}\n\n=== Plantae ===\nThe main source of Terrestrial land for the origin of the flora comes from the [[Regensburg bight]] at the margin of the [[Bohemian Massif]]. The Environment was part of the coast called [[Vindelician Land]], composed of large seashore environments, including [[River Delta]]s, [[Mangrove]]s, [[Lagoon]]s, Brackish deposits and other similar. The wood from the terrestrial margin hasn\u00b4t been studied, altrougth the ferns have been revieved.<ref>AMMON VON L. 1875. Die Jura Ablagerungen zwischen Regensburg und Passau. Theodor Ackermann, M\u00fcnchen</ref> The locality of [[Kerkhofen]] shows also influences of fluvial currents from the Massif.<ref>BRACH ERT Th. 1987. MakrofossilfUhrung der \"Siemensi-Geoden\" (Mittlerer Lias Epsilon, Unteres Toarcium) von KerkhofeniOberpfalz ( Bayern) : Neue Insekten- und Pflanzenfunde. Geologische Bl\u00e4tter NO-Bayern, 37(3-4) : 217\u2013240.</ref>\n\n====Equisetaceae====\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Genus\n! Species\n! Location\n! Stratigraphic position\n! Material\n! Notes\n! Images\n|-\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n''[[Equisetites]]''\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n*''Equisetites arenaceus''\n*''Equisetites sp.''\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n*Several locations.<ref name=\"Wilde\">Wilde, V. (2001). Die Landpflanzen-Taphoz\u00f6nose aus dem Posidonienschiefer des Unteren Jura (Schwarzer Jura [Epsilon], Unter-Toarcium) in Deutschland und ihre Deutung. Staatliches Museum f\u00fcr Naturkunde.</ref>\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\nLeaves and Branches.\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\nAffinities with [[Equisetaceae]]. Among the most common flora found on the Posidonia Shale, includes several specimens found on considered Blackish waters, being probably tolerant to high salinity environments.<ref>SALFELD, H. (1907): Fossile Land-Pflanzen der R\u00e4t- und Juraformation S\u00fcdwestdeutschlands. \u2013 Palaeontographica, 54/4: 163\u2013204, Taf. 14\u201322; Stuttgart. \u2013 (1909): Beitr\u00e4ge zur Kenntnis jurassischer Pflanzenreste aus Norddeutschland. \u2013 Palaeontographica, 56/1: 1\u201335, 2 Abb., Taf. 1\u20136. Stuttgart.</ref>\n| style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n[[File:Equisetites arenaceus 65.jpg|thumb|center|195px|''[[Equisetites]]'' arenaceus specimen]] \n|-\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n''[[Neocalamites]]''<ref>BRACHERT, T. C. (1987): Makrofossilf\u00fchrung der \u201eSiemensi-Geoden\u201c (Mittlerer Lias Epsilon, Unteres Toarcium) von Kerkhofen/Oberpfalz (Bayern): Neue Insekten- und Pflanzenfunde. \u2013 Geologische Bl\u00e4tter f\u00fcr Nordost-Bayern und angrenzende Gebiete, 37(3/4): 217\u2013240, 3 Abb., 2 Tab., Taf. 17\u201320; Erlangen.</ref>\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n*''Neocalamites merianii''\n*''Neocalamites sp.''\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n*Several locations.\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\nLeaves and Branches\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\nAffinities with [[Equisetaceae]].\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n[[File:Neocalamites merianii.JPG|thumb|center|195px|''[[Neocalamites]]'' merianii specimen]]   \n|-\n|}\n\n==== Filicopsida====\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Genus\n! Species\n! Location\n! Stratigraphic position\n! Material\n! Notes\n! Images\n|-\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n''[[Cladophlebis]]''<ref name=\"Vogellehner82\">Vogellehner, D. (1982). Zur Anatomie und Systematik von \u00abTreibh\u00f6lzern\u00bb aus dem Posidonienschiefer von Holzmaden (Schw\u00e4b. Alb).</ref>\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n*''Cladophlebis distans''\n*''Cladophlebis denticulata'' \n*''Cladophlebis haiburnenss''\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n*Holzmaden\n*Regensburg\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\nMostly leaves.\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\nAffinities with [[Osmundaceae]]. The main confirmed fern reported from the formation, being found on layers proximal to the Bohemian Massif, the dry land environment more proximal to the Posidonia Shale. \n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n[[File:Cladophlebis distans.jpg|thumb|center|195px|''[[Cladophlebis]]''  distans specimen]]\n|-\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n''[[Dictyophyllum]]''<ref name=\"Vogellehner82\"/>\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n*''Dictyophyllum acutilobum'' \n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n*Holzmaden\n*Regensburg\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\nMostly leaves.\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\nAffinities with [[Dipteridaceae]]. It\u00b4s  remains are rare.\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n[[File:Dictyophyllum acutilobum.JPG|thumb|center|195px|''[[Dictyophyllum]]'' acutilobum specimen]]\n|-\n|}\n\n====Peltaspermales====\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Genus\n! Species\n! Location\n! Stratigraphic position\n! Material\n! Notes\n! Images\n|-\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n''[[Pachypteris]]''<ref>B\u00f6ttcher, R. (1998): Leben und Tod im Meer des Posidonienschiefers. - In: E. P. J. Heizmann (Hrsg.): Erdgeschichte Mitteleurop\u00e4ischer Regionen (2). Vom Schwarzwald zum Ries, S. 83-96, 25 Abb.; M\u00fcnchen (Pfeil).</ref>\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n*''Pachypteris sp.''\n''\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n*Holzmaden\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\nOne specimen of pteridosperm frond.\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\nAffinities with [[Umkomasiaceae]]. It is related to the large Tree ferns of the Triassic & Jurassic. Includes several species from the Triassic to the Cretaceous only on Europe. Posidonia Shale Specimen is characterized for its large size.\n| style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n[[File:Pachypteris sp.jpg|thumb|center|195px|The only ''[[Pachypteris]]'' specimen know from the Posidonia Shale]]\n|-\n|}\n\n====Cycadeoidophyta====\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Genus\n! Species\n! Location\n! Stratigraphic position\n! Material\n! Notes\n! Images\n|-\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n''[[Otozamites]]''<ref name=\"Kurr\">KURR, J. G. (1845): Beitr\u00e4ge zur fossilen Flora der Juraformation W\u00fcrttembergs. \u2013 Anhang\nan: Einladungs-Schrift zu der Feier des Geburtsfestes Sr. Majest\u00e4t des K\u00f6nigs Wilhelm von W\u00fcrttemberg in der k\u00f6nigl. polytechnischen Schule zu Stuttgart den 27. September 1845: 1\u201317, 3 Taf.; Stuttgart (Guttenberg).</ref><ref>K\u00fcpper, K. (1968). Die Gattung Otozamites. Taxon, 17(5), 548\u2013552.</ref>\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n*''Otozamites gracilis''\n*''Otozamites bechei''\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n*Several locations.<ref name=\"Wilde\"/>\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\nLeaves\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\nAffinities with [[Bennettitales]]. It is the most abundant medium-sized plant on the environment. Found specially on seashore depositional settings, but also on deltaic and lagoonar environments.\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n[[File:Otozamites gracilis.jpg|thumb|center|195px|''[[Otozamites]]'' gracilis specimen from the Posidonia Shale]]\n|-\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n''[[Pterophyllum]]''<ref name=\"Kurr\"/>\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n*''Pterophyllum acutifolium''\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n*Several locations.<ref name=\"Wilde\"/>\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\nLeaves\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\nAffinities with [[Bennettitales]] \n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n[[File:Pterophyllum jaegeri 4556.jpg|thumb|center|195px|''[[Pterophyllum]]'' fossil]]  \n|-\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n''[[Zamites]]''<ref name=\"Kurr\"/>\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n*''Zamites mandelslohi''\n*''Zamites oblongifolius''\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n*Several locations.<ref name=\"Wilde\"/>\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\nLeaves\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\nAffinities with [[Bennettitales]]\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n[[File:Zamites mandelslohi.jpg|thumb|center|195px|''[[Zamites]]'' mandelslohi specimen]]\n|-\n|}\n\n====Pinophyta====\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Genus\n! Species\n! Location\n! Stratigraphic position\n! Material\n! Notes\n! Images\n|-\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n''[[Pagiophyllum]]''<ref name=\"Kurr\"/><ref>SALFELD, Palaeontographica, 54(4): 186\u2013188, Taf. 18</ref>\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n*''Pagiophyllum kurri''\n*''Pagiophyllum araucarinum''<ref>Saporta. \u2013 BARALE, Documents des Laboratoires de G\u00e9ologie Lyon, 81: 172\u2013177, Abb. 45, Taf. 49\u201350.</ref>\n*''Pagiophyllum sp.''\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n*Several locations.<ref name=\"Wilde\"/>\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\nLeaves\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\nAffinities with [[Araucariaceae]]\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n[[File:Koniferenblatt Pagiophyllum kurri.jpg|thumb|center|195px|''[[Pagiophyllum]]'' kurri specimen from Banz]] \n|-\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n''[[Cupressites]]''\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n*''Cupressites sp.''\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n*Several locations.<ref name=\"Wilde\"/>\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\nLeaves\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\nAffinities with [[Cupressaceae]]\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n|-\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n''[[Widdringtonites]]''<ref>URLICHS, WILD & ZIEGLER, Stuttgarter Beitr. Naturkde.,Reihe C, 11: Abb. 50.</ref>\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n*''Widdringtonites liasinus''\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n*Several locations.<ref name=\"Wilde\"/>\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\nLeaves\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\nA possible ancestral member of the [[Sequoioideae]] inside [[Cupressaceae]]. Was originally related to the genus  \"[[Quasisequoia]]\" couttsiae, but then changed to a sister taxa to [[Sequoia jeholensis]]. The later studies still suggest affinities with large modern redwoods. Probably the earliest member of the Sequoia tribe, distinct from Sequoiadendron and Metasequoia. \n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n[[File:Widdringtonites liasinus.JPG|thumb|center|195px|''[[Widdringtonites]]'' liasinus specimen from the Posidonia Shale]] \n|-\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n''[[Circoporoxylon]]''<ref>S\u00fcss, H., & Philippe, M. (1993). Holzanatomische Untersuchungen an einem fossilen Holz, Circoporoxylon grandiporosum M\u00fcller\u2010Stoll et Schultze\u2010Motel, aus dem Unteren Jura von Frankreich Mit 4 Abbildungen, einer Tabelle und 2 Tafeln. Feddes Repertorium, 104(7\u20108), 451\u2013463.</ref>\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n*''Circoporoxylon grandiporosum''\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n*Several locations.<ref name=\"Wilde\"/>\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\nFossil wood\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\nAffinities with [[Podocarpaceae]]\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n|-\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n''[[Cupressinoxylon]]''\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n*''Cupressinoxylon sp.''\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n*Banz<ref name=\"Wilde\"/>\n*Altdorf\n*Regensburg\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\nFossil wood\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\nAffinities with [[Sequoioideae]] inside [[Cupressaceae]]. Large wood with a morphology similar to the modern genus [[Sequoia sempervirens]]. Probably related to ''Widdringtonites liasinus'', representing the earliest representatives of the Sequoia tribe.\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n|-\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n''[[Podocarpoxylon]]''\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n*''cf. Podocarpoxylon sp.''\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n*Banz<ref name=\"Wilde\"/>\n*Altdorf\n*Regensburg\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\nFossil Wood\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\nAffinities with [[Podocarpaceae]]\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n[[File:Podocarpoxylon marchesoni.JPG|thumb|center|195px|''[[Podocarpoxylon]]'' specimen]]\n|-\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n''[[Protocupressinoxylon]]''<ref>SCHULTZE-MOTEL, J. (1960): Anatomische Untersuchungen an mesozoischen Gymnospermen-H\u00f6lzern. \u2013 Dissertation P\u00e4dagogische Hochschule Potsdam. 156 S., 25 Taf.; Potsdam. \u2013 [Unver\u00f6ffentlicht; Zitat nach VOGELLEHNER (1982), die betreffende Arbeit konnte bisher nicht eingesehen werden] \u2013 (1962): Anatomische Untersuchungen an mesozoischen Gymnospermen-H\u00f6lzern. \u2013 wilde, landpflanzen-taphocoenose aus dem posidonienschiefer 11 Wissenschaftliche Zeitschrift der P\u00e4dagogischen Hochschule Potsdam. Mathematischnaturwissenschaftliche Reihe, 7(1961/62): 343\u2013344; Potsdam. \u2013 [Autorreferat der unver\u00f6ffentlichten Dissertation]</ref>\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n*''Protocupressinoxylon catenatum''\n*''Protocupressinoxylon liasinum''\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n*Holzmaden.<ref name=\"Wilde\"/>\n*Banz\n*Altdorf\n*Regensburg\n*Bohemia\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\nFossil wood from trunk rafts\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\nAffinities with [[Podocarpaceae]]. Resembles [[Podocarpus totara]], and includes large sized trunks up to 1.7 m tall and 45&nbsp;cm wide. Large medium to large sized trees (25 m) that extent along the coastal lines of the Vindelician land. The wood from tose trunks shows insect activity, such as wood Vasps and Beetles, that had been found on the Posidonia Shale.\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n[[File:Protocupressinoxylon catenatum.JPG|thumb|center|195px|''[[Protocupressinoxylon]]'' catenatum specimen from Regensburg]]\n|-\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n''\"[[Protopinaceae]]\"''<ref>Mueller-Stoll, W. R. (1986). Evolutionary trends in gymnospermous wood structures during Mesozoic-Protopinaceous woods in the German Jurassic.</ref>\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n*''Protopinaceae sp.''\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n*Holzmaden.<ref name=\"Wilde\"/>\n*Banz\n*Altdorf\n*Regensburg\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\nFossil wood from trunk rafts\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\nDubious genera with possible affinities with the triassic wood [[Woodworthia]]. Protopinaceae is an invalid group of mostly Paleozoic Woods.<ref>Bamford, M. K., Philippe, M., & Th\u00e9venard, F. (2016). Long overdue extinction of the Protopinaceae. Review of palaeobotany and palynology, 234, 25\u201330.</ref>\n|\n[[File:Woodworthia, Late Jurassic, Chinle Formation, Petrified Forest Member, Deschutes River Canyon, Deschutes County, Oregon, USA - Houston Museum of Natural Science - DSC01832.JPG|thumb|center|195px|''[[Woodworthia]]'', example of Protopinaceae]]\n|-\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n''[[Phyllocladoxylon]]''<ref name=\"Vogellehner82\"/>\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n*''Phyllocldoxylon sp.''\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n*Several locations.<ref name=\"Vogellehner82\"/>\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\nFossil wood from trunk rafts\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\nAffinities with [[Podocarpaceae]]. Similar to the modern [[Phyllocladus aspleniifolius]]. \n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n|-\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n''[[Protophyllocladoxylon]]''<ref name=\"Vogellehner82\"/>\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n*''Protophyllocladoxylon franconicum''\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n*Several locations.<ref name=\"Wilde\"/><ref name=\"Vogellehner82\"/>\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\nFossil wood from trunk rafts\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\nAffinities with [[Podocarpaceae]]. Resembles the modern [[Phyllocladus hypophyllus]].\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n|-\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n''[[Taxodioxylon]]''<ref>M\u00dcLLER-STOLL, W. R. & SCHULTZE-MOTEL, J.(1990): Gymnospermen-H\u00f6lzer des Deutschen Jura. Teil 3: Abietoid (modern) get\u00fcpfelte H\u00f6lzer. \u2013 Zeitschrift der deutschen geologischen Gesellschaft, 141/1\u20132: 61\u201377, 2 Abb., 2 Taf.; Hannover</ref>\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n*''cf. Taxodioxylon''\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n*Holzmaden.<ref name=\"Wilde\"/>\n*Banz\n*Altdorf\n*Regensburg\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\nFossil wood from trunk rafts\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\nAffinities with the [[Taxodioideae]] family inside [[Cupressaceae]]. Resembles the modern genus [[Cryptomeria]]. Large trees probably related to the coastal settings. \n| style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n|-\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n''[[Araucarioxylon]]''<ref name=\"Crino0\">Matzke, A. T., & Maisch, M. W. (2019). Palaeoecology and taphonomy of a Seirocrinus (Echinodermata: Crinoidea) colony from the Early Jurassic Posidonienschiefer Formation (Early Toarcian) of Dotternhausen (SW Germany). Neues Jahrbuch f\u00fcr Geologie und Pal\u00e4ontologie-Abhandlungen, 291(1), 89\u2013107.</ref>\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n*''cf. Araucarioxylon''\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n*Holzmaden.<ref name=\"Crino0\"/>\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\nFossil wood from trunk rafts. Includes the largest know rafting wood on the fossil record, with a length of 13 m. The rafts where populated with Crinoid colonies, and a wide variety of organisms.\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\nAffinities with [[Araucariaceae]]\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n[[File:Araucarioxylon arizonicum reconstruccion.jpg|thumb|center|195px|''[[Araucarioxylon]]'' reconstruccion]]\n|-\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n''[[Dadoxylon]]''\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n*''Dadoxylon sp.''\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n*Holzmaden.<ref name=\"Wilde\"/>\n*Banz\n*Altdorf\n*Regensburg\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\nFossil wood from trunk rafts\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\nAffinities with [[Araucariaceae]], resembling the modern [[Wollemia]].\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n[[File:Nadelbaum Dadoxylon Stammfragment.jpg|thumb|center|195px|''[[Dadoxylon]]'' sp. from Banz]] \n|-\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n''[[Agathoxylon]]''\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n*''Agathoxylon agathiforme''<ref>Philippe, M., Barbacka, M., Gradinaru, E., Iamandei, E., Iamandei, S., K\u00e1zm\u00e9r, M., ... & Zato\u0144, M. (2006). Fossil wood and Mid-Eastern Europe terrestrial palaeobiogeography during the Jurassic\u2013Early Cretaceous interval. Review of Palaeobotany and Palynology, 142(1-2), 15\u201332.</ref>\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n*Holzmaden\n*Regensburg\n*Banz\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\nFossil wood from trunk rafts\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\nAffinities with [[Araucariaceae]], resembling the modern [[Agathis]].\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n|-\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n''[[Simplicioxylon]]''<ref>Philippe, M., Zijlstra, G., Barbacka, M., & Greguss. (1999). Greguss's morphogenera of homoxylous fossil woods: a taxonomic and nomenclatural review. Taxon, 667-676.</ref><ref>Philippe, M. (1991). Bois fossiles du jurassique de Franche-Comt\u00e9 (Doctoral dissertation, Lyon 1).</ref><ref>Polg\u00e1ri, M., Philippe, M., Sz\u00e1bo-Drubina, M., & T\u00f3th, M. (2005). Manganese-impregnated wood from a Toarcian manganese ore deposit, Epleny mine, Bakony Mts., Transdanubia, Hungary. Neues Jahrbuch f\u00fcr Geologie und Pal\u00e4ontologie-Monatshefte, 175\u2013192.</ref>\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n*''Simplicioxylon wurtembergicum''<ref>Philippe, M., Pacyna, G., Wawrzyniak, Z., Barbacka, M., Boka, K., Filipiak, P., ... & Uhl, D. (2015). News from an old wood\u2014Agathoxylon keuperianum (Unger) nov. comb. in the Keuper of Poland and France. Review of Palaeobotany and Palynology, 221, 83\u201391.</ref> \n*''Simplicioxylon cf.hungaricum''\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n*Holzmaden.\n*Banz\n*Altdorf\n*Regensburg\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\nFossil wood from trunk rafts\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;